European inflation has slipped on food
Accelerating inflation in the euro area is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
The price increase in November was higher than expected in 13 countries in the euro area, with annual inflation recorded at 3.1 percent after 2.6 percent in October, the EU’s statistical office reported.
The official forecast was only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the European Central Bank (ECB) in the United States, the British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not cut the base rate, saying that the reduction, along with rising raw material prices and easing unemployment, would lead to an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep inflation rates below, but close to, 2%.
According to one analyst, the ECB is trapped in its 22nd trap: “We need to talk down inflation so that it does not have to act on this subject later.
In Germany, inflation in November is a record of 3.3 percent for 12 years; in Spain, it rose from 3.6 to 4.1.
Euro zone inflation has been driven by rising food and energy prices.
Future wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and soybean prices have reached the highest value since 1973.
Food oil and dairy products also had to be paid significantly more in 2007.
Oil prices on the world market rose 52 percent this year, and last month it cost almost $100 a barrel of black gold.
According to the ECB, inflation will jump from 2.1 to 2.5 per cent in 2008, but will fall to 1.9 per cent in 2009.
Analysts say the 12-month inflation rate will remain at around 3 percent in the next 3-4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, it is expected that the ECB has reduced interest rates twice during 2008.
