They save on disinfectants in many places
This year, more than 1,000 infections have been reported in hospitals, mainly due to inadequate use of antibiotics.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the congestion of beds and the overload of staff do not favour stopping infections, says the head of department of the National Epidemiology Centre.
They also save on disinfectants in many places.
Recently, MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of John’s Hospital.
After a serious accident, a man was found to be resistant to antibiotics.
The patient was isolated.
There was a similar infection at the beginning of the year.
An injured person in a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly thereafter he had to return with MRSA infection, and an important surgery has not been performed since then because of the bacteria in his system.
This year, by December 10, 1094 hospital infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, Chief Medical Officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that so many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have certainly been registered in hospitals, and the rest is unknown.
About two thirds (683 infections) of infections were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin resistant Staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without causing disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. sore throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infection) respond well to antibiotics and can be cured well.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, bacteria that respond well to antibiotics develop a highly resistant bacteria that spreads rapidly under inadequate hospital conditions.
In particular, when the immune system is temporarily or permanently impaired, it may cause serious hospital infections such as wound infection or sepsis in elderly or low body weight patients.
According to the medical director of John’s Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infection, such infections belong to the daily practice of hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the disease, MRSA is only not there, said Tibor Nyulasi, where the presence of the pathogen is not investigated.
Resistant to antibiotics
"We isolate such patients, the nursing staff provides the patient with rubber gloves and masks, and we have the right antibiotics for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Patients admitted to the hospital are pre-examined to see if MRSA is present in their bodies, but the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of hospital infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current domestic hospital conditions and conditions are not favourable for preventing the development and spread of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection typically occurs in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should check patients entering and isolate patients carrying MRSA immediately.
However, microbiological sampling is not in fashion in Hungarian hospitals.
It also plays a role in this, that the National Health Insurance Fund does not finance these tests.
Most cases will thus come to light if the patient has a detectable MRSA infection, said the head of department at the epidemiological centre.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the proper use of antibiotics in human medicine, and there are domestic guidelines for the treatment of individual infections and pathologies.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medicines, but hospitals do not always comply with this.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and primary care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Save on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transmitted from one patient to another through the mediation of medical personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also significant shortcomings in hospitals.
MRSA spreads with droplet infection and contact, but in domestic hospital conditions it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
In fact, the wards are often crowded, and the beds are often very close to each other, even though from an epidemiological point of view, patients should be at least 1.5 meters apart.
Unfortunately, we can also experience, noted Karolina Böröcz, that in hospitals in an unfavorable financial situation they save on disinfectants, there are few nurses, there are many patients, so there is an even greater chance of developing infections.
According to Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate precautions are taken, there is less infection or the spread of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government program against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection causes huge expenses for health insurance companies, so they fight it everywhere.
In England, for example, it included the prevention and reduction of MRSA in the government programme.
The program appears to be successful, and according to the data published, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The priorities of the European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) include the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and hospital infections caused by such pathogens.
