Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the expert meetings will be completed on Tuesday, and on Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the international climate regime after 2012 will continue with the negotiations of the ministers.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world are discussing the Bali Roadmap, which provides for efforts following the emission reduction period set out in the Kyoto Protocol until 2012.
This is currently being debated between developing and developed countries.
The United States has also indicated that it does not currently want to negotiate precise figures, although it is inclined to agree to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
Another big question of the conference is whether developed countries will undertake, in addition to reducing emissions, to provide both financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
There has also been an agreement on aid to developing countries.
The fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be managed by a board of 16 members, expected to be within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF), according to the Market and Profit.
6 percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Minister of Environment and Water Gábor Fodor supports the EU’s efforts to preserve its flagship role in global climate protection efforts and to promote the establishment of a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU will commit to a 20% reduction in its greenhouse gas emissions by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, regardless of the success of the conclusion of the "post-2012 agreement", and is ready to take up to 30 percent reduction if other large developed regions of the world and developing countries are willing to take on commitments in accordance with their responsibilities and capabilities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that in 1997 the countries that acceded to the Kyoto Protocol set a total reduction of 5.2 percent, including the EU - 15 Member States at the time - took up minus 8 percent.
The Hungarian obligation is a 6 percent greenhouse gas emission reduction compared to the 1985-87 period, which Hungary will meet.
The stakes are high in Bali, as the long-term international climate policy agreement must be concluded within two years, otherwise its entry into force would surely be delayed beyond 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not immediately be followed by another international emission reduction system, the IPCC, the UN Nobel Peace Prize winner, international scientific body on climate change, pointed out in its latest report.
By doing so, emissions reductions would be delayed and an increase in the Earth’s average temperature above 2 Celcius degrees would be inevitable, which scientists believe would have extremely serious and irreversible consequences.
