Political Capital: Hungarian Guard raises country’s risk
With the support of Jobbik Hungary Movement, the activities of the Hungarian Guard, founded in August of this year, increased the political risk of Hungary and the region in several respects, according to the Political Capital Risk Analysis Division (Risk Analysis Division).
In the company's "risk warning", they wrote that the greatest political risk in connection with the activities of the Hungarian Guard is that "the already existing ethnic tension between the Roma and the non-Gypsy population in Hungary can develop violent ethnic clashes in the short term".
The main reason for this is that the political strategy of the Hungarian Guard is likely to provoke such an act, the research institute added.
As they wrote, this can be traced back to one of the main failures of Hungarian political actors: "the public debate on the Roma issue was handed over by public actors to representatives of radical and extremist political groups who could build a political strategy on the Gypsy-Hungarian conflict".
This deepens the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists, and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts, they believe.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activities of the Hungarian Guard have "significantly worsened the image of Hungary abroad, mainly as regards faith in the stability and democratic development of the country".
They remind us that from the autumn of 2006, it was part of the reorganization of radical and far-right groups in Hungary that received increasing publicity and momentum, that from the summer of 2007 several organisations calling themselves "national self-defense" associations were formed in Hungary.
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as NGOs, while openly proclaiming the preparation of their members, even armed ones, for defence (catastrophic, defence, law enforcement) tasks, and also on the grounds of the inadequacy of the police, the army, the state," they added.
They noted that this is done in accordance with the method of putting various political aspirations in civilian robes based on the political and anti-partisanism of society.
The emphasis on civility and the form of association therefore serve not only to avoid the legal pitfalls of judicial registration in the case of these associations, but also as a political strategy.
According to the analysis, the activities of the Hungarian Guard are also a risk-enhancing factor for neighbourhood relations.
"In recent months, the Hungarian Guard has been referred to as a potential threat in several neighbouring states, and the ultranationalist political actors of some neighbouring countries want to justify their own anti-Hungarian policy by referring to the establishment of the Hungarian Guard.
This has an impact on the political stability of the region," they added.
According to the research institute, the formation of the Hungarian Guard is not a unique phenomenon in Eastern Central Europe, so political risks have increased for the region as a whole.
As they wrote, the operation of the Hungarian Guard is similar to that of the Bulgarian National Guard, the establishment of which was announced in August 2007 by the far-right Bulgarian National Union (BNU).
The formation of the Bulgarian Guard is due to the mass Roma riots that broke out in a quarter of Sofia (Krasna Poljana).
BNU took advantage of this decision to establish a guard, saying that the purpose of the organization is "national self-defense".
“In the last 17 years, there has been a ‘Gypsy terror’ in Bulgaria, but the state has remained inactive and indifferent,” he said.
They added that the initiative provoked a heated debate in the Bulgarian public.
As they wrote, the increased risk of ethnic clashes is indicated by the fact that some Roma organisations in Bulgaria have announced that they are creating their own guard as a resistance.
Since the operation of the Hungarian Guard so far shows similarities with the operation of the Bulgarian National Guard, it cannot be excluded that the Roma in Hungary will respond to the threat in the same way by organising their own self-defense, read the risk warning of Political Capital.
Attila Juhász, Director of Research at Political Capital, said to the interest of the telegraph office: risk analysis is one of the activities of the research institute.
As he said, they publish their risk analysis every year, and if they experience something that may affect the change in risk, they inform the public, as in this case, by issuing a risk warning.
