Remarkable Memories
After more than 60 years of encryption, the Bad Arolsen archive has become public, documenting the fate of 17 and a half million victims of the Hitler regime.
The 47 million archive documents, which occupy 27 kilometers of shelves in Bad Arolsen, Hessen Province, have so far only been researched for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. they have only provided unique and name-based access to former victims or their descendants.
The eleven states that managed the archives, including Germany, France, Israel and the United States, agreed to open the archives to researchers and historians in May 2006.
After all the states ratified the treaty, the archive was opened yesterday.
Confidential information
The opening of the Bad Arolsen archives allows historians to conduct research "on the relocation of prisoners, the inhabitants of camps and the health of forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, director of the archive managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross.
Until now, several states, including Germany, have opposed the publication of documents, as they contain names and thus confidential information.
This may include, for example, the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some deported victims.
The list of concentration camps and the arrest orders issued by the Gestapo began to be collected after the war for practical reasons. The aim was to search for civilians deported or sentenced to forced labour and possibly provide evidence of their internment, which allowed them to receive compensation.
In Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent workers are currently processing tens of thousands of individual needs.
However, part of the scientific community does not consider the opening of the Bad Arolsen archive to be of paramount importance.
“These documents are basically nothing new,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Anti-Semitism Research at the Technical University of Berlin in 2006.
