More fears about the Russian-Ukrainian gas dispute
The gas dispute between Ukraine and Russia has resumed, which may also affect Russian fuel to be transported to Western Europe.
Most of the Russian gas exported to the European Union (EU) is transferred through Ukraine, and disputes between the two nations are always closely monitored.
Kiev said that if Moscow raises the price of gas to be paid by Ukrainians, they will also hit Russia with higher transit costs.
As a result of a previous debate between the two countries last year, supplies to EU countries have decreased.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow relates to the attempt by the Ukrainian government and the Russian state-owned gas monopoly Gazprom to negotiate an agreement on the price of gas to be paid by Ukraine to Russia in 2008.
Gazprom stated that it would have to implement a 50% increase in gas extracted from neighbouring Turkmenistan compared to the price agreement concluded with Ukraine for 2008.
According to analysts, this could mean a 40% increase in the price of the shipment from Gazprom for Ukraine.
"It is important to argue in line with one of the most important transit states for natural gas during the negotiations," Ukrainian Minister of Economy Anatoly Kinah told Reuters.
“The changes in gas prices should certainly be linked to our debate on the extent of the costs of transits through Ukraine (and to Western Europe).
As a result of the recent major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom closed the gas tap leading to Ukraine in January 2006.
This resulted in a domino-like decrease in exports to Western Europe, which also greatly increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union’s gas supply.
Russia has the largest natural gas reserves in the world, but most of them are still unexplored.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply with natural gas from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet states in Central Asia.
The NHS “must monitor foreign workers”
The Scottish NHS Committees must improve checks on the criminal records of workers from outside Europe, a supervisory body said.
The proposal was made by Chief Accountant Robert Black after a foreign national doctor in Scotland was linked to the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that NHS Scotland does not have accurate data on the number of overseas employees.
At the same time, in his report, he pointed out, through a sample of five health authorities, key controls that have been properly carried out.
Following the attack on Glasgow Airport, the chief auditor checked the list of employees recruited outside the European Economic Area.
Bilal Abdullah, a 28-year-old Iraqi doctor at Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after a jeep hit the main terminal of the building.
Abdullah was one of three doctors questioned by the Old Bailey Court in October on charges of car bombing attempts in the UK.
The NHS Committees shall verify the existence of qualifications and work experience of the workers concerned and the availability of permits to work in the United Kingdom for their employees from overseas countries before starting employment.
Although the Scottish Health Committees use Disclosure Scotland to verify criminal records, the agency is not entitled to obtain such information from outside the territory of Great Britain.
Among other things, the chief auditor's report proposed that the committees should introduce the Criminal Records Office's guidance, which facilitates the audit process with different overseas countries for the employer.
"Although evidence of such checks has been found in the records of the staff, they are not carried out regularly," the report says.
According to Black, the Scottish NHS performs its own pre-employment screening procedure at a high level, adding: "Our report highlights the areas of the system that can be developed in order to provide up-to-date information on the number of NHS overseas staff."
According to Dr. Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, it is “extremely unrealistic” to use pre-employment checks to identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
“According to the report, the pre-employment checks currently in place in NHS Scotland are working well, and the value of the proposals is not yet transparent,” he added.
According to the Scottish health authorities, the majority of their overseas employees, consisting of doctors and nurses, currently account for 1,161 people.
However, the chief auditor pointed out that the figures are likely to be higher, which can be partly explained by the fact that the Commissions have a problem identifying employees on indefinite leave.
The investigation also showed that the control procedures introduced in the Ayrshire and Arran regions, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and the NHS authorities in Lothian operate in a highly coordinated manner.
These procedures covered the verification of passports, work permits and evidence of professional qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently examining the directive and guidance on pre-employment controls for NHS employees from overseas countries.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: "I was very pleased that this task was carried out after the attack on Glasgow airport.
He further added that the Scottish Government, in cooperation with the Health Committees, will take into account the proposals contained in the report and will ensure that the up-to-date guidance on pre-employment checks on the entire staff, including those from overseas, reflects the best practical application. The updated version is planned to be published next month.
