The climate of Venus can provide an outlook on the future of the Earth
Scientists found yesterday that Venus could once provide pleasant living conditions.
Data from a European orbiting spacecraft suggests that this planet is much more of an Earth's capricious twin brother than we thought.
Venus is the closest planet next door to Earth.
The size of the two planets is almost the same and their orbit is similar, although Venus is slightly closer to the Sun.
According to scientists today, billions of years ago Venus could have been ruled by living conditions very similar to that of the Earth, and even habitable conditions could have been given.
However, due to the extremely high carbon dioxide greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion caused by solar radiation and the lower rotation speed of the planet, Venus has entered a completely different developmental path.
Today, the water has evaporated from the planet, its surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it is destroyed by hurricane winds and lightning storms.
The findings of the European Space Agency's Venus Express space probe, based on a year's study of the planet, paint a sobering picture of how similar catastrophic climate changes can occur on Earth.
Fred Taylor, a professor at the Department of Physics at Oxford University, who is also one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is beginning to show why the climate of Venus differs so greatly from that of Earth, despite the fact that the two planets are otherwise very similar in structure.
“With the help of our new data, it was possible to develop a scenario for the formation of Venus billions of years ago, when it could have had living conditions similar to Earth.
