Is the Second Market Mortgage Market Crisis Threatening America’s Credit Card Market?
If there is blood in the water, it is natural for sharks to appear nearby.
Now that the U.S. housing market is indisposed, predators are focusing on the country's credit card market.
Goldman Sachs analysts believe that if the mortgage crisis infects other forms of retail loans, the credit card market could lose up to $99 billion.
The signs of tension are clearly visible.
Both the write-down rate showing the rate of unrecoverable loans and the default rate indicating the rate of late payments over 30 days have increased.
HSBC reported a loss of $1.4 billion in the US consumer finance segment last month, partly due to the financial weakness of cardholders.
At the same time, panic is premature.
The rate of write-offs and late payments remains low.
The late payment rate of 3.89% calculated by the Moody's credit rating agency for the third quarter is one full percentage point lower than the historical average.
The decline in rates can be partly explained by technical factors.
The change in the US rules on individual insolvency in 2005 resulted in a sudden decrease in the number of insolvency applicants, but at the same time caused a large loss in the credit card market; the number of bankruptcy applications (and thus the write-down rate) is expected to increase again, regardless of whether the total terms of borrowing deteriorate or not.
The payment rate, which shows the rate of monthly credit repayment for consumers, is also solid on the market.
In addition, trust in credit card-backed securities is quite strong, despite the paralysis in other areas of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney at TowerGroup estimates that the 2007 emissions volume will be 25% higher than last year.
The signs of the impact of the mortgage crisis on the credit card market are clear: consumers are increasing the debt on credit cards to repay home loans.
At the same time, card issuers primarily monitor the movement of money and not the value of assets, so the fall in housing prices does not necessarily cause a change in the creditworthiness of borrowers.
Creditors may also benefit from the situation.
If the property is worth less than the value of the mortgage, the incentive for consumers to repay the credit will be reduced; as a result, the repayment of debts on credit cards will move forward in the priority ranking.
By changing interest rates or credit limits, card issuers can adapt to changing conditions faster and more flexibly than mortgage lenders.
Theoretically, this should reduce the risk of a sudden re-price of assets.
“It’s unlikely that one day we’ll wake up to fully reevaluate the loans,” says Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a subprime-like sudden crisis in the credit card market is less likely, the risk of a gradual decline is much greater.
If declining housing prices and a decline in lending put America in a recession, the industry is no doubt facing a grim future.
It's worth watching those predatory fins.
