Venus is the Earth's diabolical twin
Despite the harsh atmosphere of Venus, it is more similar to Earth than previously assumed: In its atmosphere, the European space probe "Venus Express" discovered lightning and on its polar circles wind vortexes such as those that occur on Earth in winter.
For nearly three decades, scientists have assumed that Venus is lightning.
The European space probe "Venus Express" provided evidence - discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere: Lightning on Venus spreads from cloud to cloud at a height of 56 kilometers, reports Christpher Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles, in the columns of the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "old soup theory", the formation of life on Earth was caused by lightnings: According to the theory, thunderstorms triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If life ever existed there, it could have been in very early times," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institute in Washington, D.C.
At present, there can hardly be a living organism on the surface of Venus: The atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, and temperature values sometimes reach 500 degrees.
"Venus may be Earth's infernal twin brother, but it's still her twin brother," Russell said.
The main question of the Esa mission is why Venus, so similar in mass and size to Earth, is on a completely different path of development.
The launch of Venus Express in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus research, because since the early 1990s, no probe has been on the road specifically to find this planet.
The latest research results presented in several "Nature" articles prove not only the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also point out that the similarity of the neighboring planet to Earth is greater than we initially assumed," Esa said.
In addition to the already known Arctic whirlwind, researchers have discovered an even faster-moving cloud vortex in the South Pole.
The phenomenon is reminiscent of the air currents of the Earth's winter hemisphere, according to the research team led by Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmoca Institute.
The second innermost planet in the solar system is almost the same mass as Earth's, and with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, it is almost the size of Earth.
The celestial body, also called the Evening Star, orbits the sun in less than 225 days.
However, it turns much slower around its own tenge: a Venus day lasts 243 days on earth.
Although Venus’ surface temperature of 460 degrees Celsius, coupled with 92 bar pressure, is hardly reminiscent of Earth, scientists assume that both planets were formed under completely similar conditions.
They both had water on them, which remained on Earth as an ocean, while Venus went to the universe.
And while carbon dioxide on Earth is bound in carbonate rocks, on Venus it forms a large part of the atmosphere.
