These aren't Warhol's crates.
Anyone who connects the concepts of Sweden and wooden crates to each other is thinking of Ikea, not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently, wooden crates produced in Sweden cast a dark shadow on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four "Stockholm type" Brillo Box listed in this is fake.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the originality of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo Boxes a few months ago, now the internal investigation of Moderna Museet in Stockholm has come to a sobering conclusion: The six copies of "Brillo Box" donated to Moderna Museet by Pontus Hultén, former museum director in 1995 - and most likely a hundred more "Stockholm-type" Brillo Box on the international art market.
The history is a confusing chain of long and complicated artistic and board stunts.
Warhol created the first "Brillo Boxai" in New York in 1964 - painted wooden crates based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the soap powder "Brillo".
At an exhibition of his works held in Moderna Museet in 1968, with Warhol's consent, hundreds of cardboard Brillo crates were exhibited: these (for cost-saving reasons) were not from Warhol, but were transported directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It wasn't about works of art, it was about their templates, simple exhibits.
At the same time, Warhol granted permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not issued in Moderna Museet.
The witnesses of the time now speak of about fifteen crates that, as authenticated Original-Andy-Warhol-Brillo-Box, were entitled to enter the history of art and auction under the designation "Stockholm type".
Some of them were auctioned for over $100,000.
The problem, however, is that Pontus Hultén, the legendary museum director, later falsely claimed that in 1968 a hundred wooden crates were manufactured and exhibited in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hulten's 105 crates were only manufactured in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg in Malmo.
At that time, however, Warhol had been dead for three years.
In addition to the six Brillo Boxes owned by the museum, Lars Byström, the main monument administrator of Moderna Museet, examined three Swedish privately owned boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: The pressed chipboards were first laid down and sanded, and the white oil paint was then brushed up.
On the other hand, the structure of the copies from 1990 shows that the paint was applied directly to the chipboard with a paint roller without foundation - and it is not oil, it is acrylic paint.
"These crates were not certified by the artist, so they should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol Brillo Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "Unless the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York decides otherwise, Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
The Authentication Board, of course, announced in June that it would investigate the "serious accusations" raised in connection with soap dust crates.
Since then, however, they have been wrapped in unrelenting silence.
